bib_record.title: Fast neutron scattering on Gallium target at 14.8 MeV

free_txt: In order to make the background correction, two runs
of measurement with sample in and sample out were
performed for each set up.
A detector positioned at 135 deg with respect
to the D+ beam was used to monitor the neutron yield
by counting the associated alpha particles.
A BC501A (5.08 cm x 2.54 cm) scintillation
detector used for leakage neutron detection, was
placed at 7.98 m from the neutron source at
approximately zero degree, which is used to monitor
the accelerator pulse shape spectrum.
Total uncertainties
Neutron detection efficiency about 3%
Scattering angle ambiguity <= 1%
Absolute normalization calibration below 1%
Neutrons were produced by 300 keV D+ beam. The
average beam current was about 30 uA. The pulse width
of the D+ beam during this experiment was kept around
3 ns and the repetition rate was 1.5 MHz.
Leakage neutron spectra ware measured with the
flight path of 8.30 m and 8.67 m for 60 and 120 deg.
For detection threshold determination
For neutron-gamma discrimination
Natural Ga was composed of 60.11% Ga-69 and 39.89%
Ga-71. Two self-supported solid Ga samples were made
as a cylindrical shape with 13 cm x 3.2 cm and 13 cm
x 6.4 cm.
Data presented by first author
